Content:
[link: #table-of-content] íŸ@e1a4eef59b9aeb1f3371dd63977bae3b69e832eadafa2a857a9766c3d55eefd7⁄hTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.1
Path: ]
Content:
[link: #table-of-content] Tilde expansion in the name of an external command was inadvertently removed from 0.94.0, so these no longer worked:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
~/bin/foo
^~/bin/bar
run-external ~/bin/baz

```
This behavior has been restored by 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13001] #13001
. We chose not to allow the following, for now (these still don't expand):
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
^"~/bin/foo"
^$"~/bin/($env.BIN_NAME)"
# and run-external with the same

```
This is to be consistent with our behavior in other places where quoted strings usually don't cause expansion of extra path features. It is possible to use 
``path expand``
 instead:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
^("~/bin/foo" | path expand)

```
but we would like to make this more ergonomic somehow in a future release.
íŸ@4f9b112b88544153d39d6a755f607124baf74cc9f718869f291c24458d944018⁄aTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.1
Path: ]
Content:
``do``
[link: #table-of-content] A bug has existed for a little while when using 
``do``
 with a closure that takes rest args and also takes required or optional args.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
do { |a, b, ...c| print $a $b $c } 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8

```
Before the patch, this would print 
``1``
, 
``2``
, and then 
``[5 6 7 8]``
, as the non-rest args were counted incorrectly. 
[link: https://github.com/WindSoilder] @WindSoilder
 fixed this in 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13002] #13002
, and that fix is included in this release. Thanks!
íŸ@5143625f380ff3816226e94c68e3d32284434cf028b8ecb7db1f15259bc25b5d⁄ˆTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.1
Path: ]
Content:
``path type``
[link: #table-of-content] In 0.94.0, we changed 
``path type``
 to return an error for non-existent paths rather than an empty string, but we didn't communicate this change thoroughly enough and it broke some tools like 
``zoxide``
. We've decided to go back to the previous behavior for now and revisit this later.
Fixed by 
[link: https://github.com/IanManske] @IanManske
 in 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13006] #13006
.
íŸ@ba6798bf756004a7d5497c4f97613a269f4ebff258dd501353cd9a95577f92b1⁄”Title: title: Nushell 0.94.1
Path: ]
Content:
[link: #table-of-content] This escape sequence is used to tell terminals where the current directory is. This is helpful for terminals that open new tabs in the same directory, e.g. "Duplicate Tab" in Windows Terminal. A slash was being added incorrectly to the beginning here, which broke Windows.
Fixed by 
[link: https://github.com/fdncred] @fdncred
 in 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/12994] #12994
.
íŸ@81ec1d77a85351c75ea126965ec389fcd5d72b99c657e0a23dd85ebcb2707654⁄ÜTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.1
Path: ]
Content:
``cmd.exe``
[link: #table-of-content] Properly escaping command arguments on Windows is 
[link: https://flatt.tech/research/posts/batbadbut-you-cant-securely-execute-commands-on-windows/] complicated
, and we weren't correctly rejecting certain potentially unsafe arguments to the 
``cmd.exe``
 builtins we support (such as 
``mklink``
). As we would prefer that you only have to learn one set of escaping rules to use Nushell properly, this is undesirable behavior, so 
[link: https://github.com/IanManske] @IanManske
 has fixed it in 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13009] #13009
.
